    "Html": "Hi,<br>\r\n<br>\r\nI currently have an ObservableCollection&lt;T&gt; that is binded to both a WPF Toolkit Datagrid and an ItemsControl.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nIn order for the user to be abble to insert new values into the datagrid I add (in code-behind) the first item to the Collection. However, by doing so, The itemsControl gets not one but two items??!!???....<br>\r\n<br>\r\nEven If I delete the datagrid first row.. it will always stay one item of the ItemsControl (One is allways there - the ItemTemplate, it seems)??!!....<br>\r\n<br>\r\nCan you understand what It went wrong?? Or a way to fix this?<br>\r\n<br>\r\nNOTE: If I don't add in code behind the item, the itemsControl works correctly (but the user doe not have the option of inserting new data (rows) in the datagrid.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nThanks in advance<br>\r\n",
    "PostedDate": "2009-03-24T10:57:14.577-07:00",
    "UserRole": null,
    "MarkedAsAnswerDate": null
  },
  {
    "Id": "171468",
    "ThreadId": "51144",
    "Html": "You should not need to add items manually. If T is a type with a default constructor (a constructor with no arguments), then the ListCollectionView that is automatically created for the ObservableCollection&lt;T&gt; should be able to create the new item.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nThe ListCollectionView will also have a new item placeholder to represent the new rowÂ before it's actually added. The placeholder is just an object, so it will not be of type T. Perhaps this is what you are seeing in the ItemsControl.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nBen\r\n",
    "PostedDate": "2009-03-24T12:39:25.85-07:00",
    "UserRole": null,
    "MarkedAsAnswerDate": null
  },
  {
    "Id": "171739",
    "ThreadId": "51144",
    "Html": "Thanks for you input Ben,<br>\r\n<br>\r\nI'm currently using the following XAML code:<br>\r\n<br>\r\n&lt;toolkit:DataGrid x:Name=&quot;dg&quot; CanUserAddRows=&quot;True&quot; CanUserDeleteRows=&quot;True&quot; ItemsSource=&quot;{Binding}&quot; AutoGenerateColumns=&quot;False&quot;&gt;<br>\r\n...<br>\r\n&lt;toolkit:DataGrid&gt;<br>\r\n<br>\r\nAnd, on the code-behind:<br>\r\n<br>\r\nObservableCollection&lt;sObject&gt; LetsTry = new ObservableCollection&lt;sObject&gt;<br>\r\n<br>\r\nLetsTry.Add(new&nbsp; sObject());<br>\r\ndg.DataContext = LetsTry;<br>\r\n<br>\r\nBy using this, I start with two rows (so far, the only way I've managed to be able to add rows on the datagrid in run mode).. You say it's possible to have he same functionality (being able to add rows) without adding in code behind a new sObject?<br>\r\n<br>\r\nIf so, please can you tell me how? (It's been a big headache for me -- I'm a rookie so many things are headaches .. :P)<br>\r\n<br>\r\nThanks in advance<br>\r\n",
    "PostedDate": "2009-03-25T02:13:21.99-07:00",
    "UserRole": null,
    "MarkedAsAnswerDate": null
  },
  {
    "Id": "171968",
    "ThreadId": "51144",
    "Html": "Since CanUserAddRows is true, you are seeing the item that you added and the new item placeholder row. The new item placeholder row allows users to type into that row to create new items. If you add no items (remote the line LetsTry.Add(new sObject()), you should see only the new item placeholder row.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nBen\r\n",
    "PostedDate": "2009-03-25T11:29:16.013-07:00",
    "UserRole": null,
    "MarkedAsAnswerDate": null
  },
